## Tools Used

- Gobuster (AttackBox).
- Wordlists (Dirbuster, SecLists).
- DNS configuration files.
- Browser developer tools (to inspect requests).

## Findings

- Gobuster efficiently discovers hidden directories, files, subdomains, and vhosts.
- Enumeration relies heavily on wordlists.
- Misconfigured DNS or missing entries in /etc/hosts can cause failures.
- High thread counts improve speed but may trigger detection.
- False positives in vhost mode can be filtered by response length.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Limit enumeration attempts to avoid detection.
- Use appropriate wordlists for context (small vs. large).
- Monitor server logs for brute force activity.
- Harden web servers against directory listing and default vhosts.
- Implement rate limiting and WAF rules.
- Secure DNS and virtual host configurations.

## Conclusion

- Gobuster is a versatile tool for reconnaissance in penetration testing.
- Understanding its modes (dir, dns, vhost) is essential for effective use.
- Proper environment setup (DNS, wordlists, threads) ensures accurate results.
- Defensive measures (rate limiting, monitoring, WAF, strong configurations) mitigate enumeration risks.
